Inflation in Europe has jumped because of food
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November’s price growth in 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected, with annual inflation at 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, the Union’s statistical office said.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the US, UK and Canadian banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the basic interest rate, with the fact that a reduction along with rising raw material prices and falling unemployment would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below 2%, but close to it.
According to one of the analysts, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to "derail" inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation stood at 3.3 percent, a 15-year record; in Spain, it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has skyrocketed due to sharply rising food and energy prices.
The futures price of wheat rose by 88 percent, and the soy price reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil in world markets this year rose by 52 percent and last month, one barrel of black gold was already worth nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 per cent in 2008 to 2.5 per cent this year, but will already fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will continue to be approximately 3 percent, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
