In many places, they are saved on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infections have been reported in hospitals, mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff stopping the disease do not help, says the mayor of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, it is also saved on disinfectants.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatology department of St. John’s Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been found in a man who got into the hospital after a serious traffic accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same place at the beginning of the year.
A patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after he had to return with an MRSA infection and due to the bacteria in his body, one important operation could not yet be performed.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National System of Nesocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czov<0xC3><0xA1>, the National Epidemiological Center’s first female prime minister.
This means that so many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals with certainty, others are not known.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant gold staphylococcus.
The bacteria Staphylococcus aureus (SA) carries a third of the people in the nose without it, without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, early infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are given to an excessive or inappropriate extent, it develops from a bacterium that responds well to antibiotics, a bacterium that is very resistant to antibiotics and that spreads rapidly under inappropriate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of transient or permanent malfunction of the immune system in patients with a weakened body, low body weight or in patients over the years, it can cause serious hospital infections, such as an early infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the chief doctor of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such an infection belongs in hospitals to daily practice.
"The infection must not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not only there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the causative agent of the disease is not investigated."
Resists Antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the treatment staff treats them in rubber gloves and in a mask and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined whether MRSA is present in their body, however, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in domestic hospitals are not conducive to the prevention of the emergence and spread of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Since this infection occurs significantly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor admitted patients and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, the collection of microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not fashionable.
It also plays a role in the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases are detected if the patient suffers from a palpable MRSA infection, said the head of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, morbidity.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, or microbiological testing should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not follow this in all cases.
Sampling of microbiological samples is even rarer in basic or outpatient treatment of patients, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czov<0xC3><0xA1> said.
It is stored on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most often spread among patients through medical personnel.
Therefore, it plays a very important role in hand washing and the use of gloves and masks, but there are serious shortcomings in hospitals, too.
MRSA is transmitted by a droplet infection and by touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients under the conditions of home hospitals.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
As Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czov<0xC3><0xA1> noted, unfortunately, we can also meet with the fact that in hospitals that are in an adverse material situation, they save on disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients, thus increasing the chances of infections.
According to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czov<0xC3><0xA1>, where the necessary protective measures are followed, similar infections are demonstrably less or the further spread of the disease can be stopped.
The Government Program Against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is fought against everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has written a program to prevent MRSA, or reduce its occurrence.
The program appears to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England show a decreasing trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks prevention of multi-drug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) as one of its priorities, i.e. hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
