The activity of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarorsz<0xC3><0xA1>gért movement in August of this year, according to the Risk Analysis Division of the Political Capital Institute, immediately increased the political risk of Hungary and the whole region in several respects.
In the "risk warning" developed by the company, it is written: in connection with the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is that "the already existing ethnic tension between the Roma and non-Romani population of Hungary can soon lead to violent ethnicities".
The main reason is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably aimed at provoking such an action - adds the research institute.
As he writes, all this can be explained by one of the greatest negligence of Hungarian political leaders: "public discussion on the Roma question was left to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian contradiction."
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts – the institute judges.
In addition, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, according to the research institute, due to the great attention of both domestic and foreign media, "has greatly distorted the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards the belief in the stability of the country and its democratic development".
As part of the reorganisation of Hungarian radical and far-right groups, which has been receiving increasing publicity and vehemence since the autumn of 2006, several organisations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, which call themselves "National Home Guard" associations.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil associations, while openly declaring - even armed - the readiness of their members to carry out defensive tasks (in the event of natural disasters, invasion of the country, disruption of order), in addition to pointing out the incapacity of the police, the army, or the state," he said.
He further notes: all this is happening in a way that seeks to wrap up the various political efforts built on society’s opposition to politics and parties in civilian clothes.
The emphasis on civility and the form of the association, therefore, in the case of these groups, is not only used to avoid legal obstacles to judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk-increasing factor in terms of neighbouring relations.
