The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
More than a hundred billion dollars will be put into the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, banks attract interest rates for which they are willing to lend money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will send $40 billion to the auction, and then make another twenty-four more available to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of 11 September that the central banks of individual states have agreed on such a coordinated procedure to prevent or reduce the consequences of the financial crisis.
“This step is intended to address the biggest economic challenge, the growing lack of free capital that banks could borrow,” Bernard Baumohl of Economic Outlook Group, a consulting firm, wrote in a report to clients.
"Coordinated central bank action has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent," Baumohl said in a statement.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to outstanding loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect another $1 billion in losses.
“Central banks must be really afraid of what might happen when they decide to do this,” said ABN Chief Economist Amro Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will also lend to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with potential impacts on global economic growth.
The central banks thus decided after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used to lend money on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still concerned about lending money to each other, despite the fact that the central banks of the US, Canada and Britain had reduced their interest rates several times during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as another interest rate drop," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
