Congress approves MiFID roll-out effective November 1
Concurrent with the parliamentary negotiations that ended today with a vote in Congress on the Senate's amendments to the bill, the government has submitted to a public hearing the regulations that are developing the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the parties unanimously highlighted the efforts of Members and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to guarantee the protection of investors and the detailed regulation of the activities of entities necessary for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernisation of financial markets and at the same time strengthens investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the individual supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable financial advisory services to be provided to both specialised companies and natural or legal persons, and will create a new type of financial service provider (ESIS), financial advisory company (AFI), which join companies with securities, brokerages and brokerages.
In addition, the number of systems for performing operations with financial instruments is being expanded by adding multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with current stockbrokers.
The law further obliges investment service providers to disseminate on the market information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and ways of coping with risk, and requires them to keep a record of all the operations carried out to simplify supervision by CNMV.
During the discussion in the Congressional Trade Commission, several amendments were included, among which stand out the fact that securitised receivables were considered a "complex" financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what occurred in the US with high-risk mortgages.
In addition, the transposition of the Directive has been used to legally determine the functions that can be held by bachelors in the field of economics and business management 30 years after the Royal Decree, which specifies professional functions reserved for economists, was approved in 1977.
At the same time, the Senate has included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
